  "prompt_type": "cognitive",
  "prompt_text": "Explain the concept of Big-O notation. Rank the following: O(n!), O(2^n), O(n^2), O(n log n), O(n), O(log n), O(1).",
  "response_text": "Big-O notation is a way to describe the complexity or efficiency of an algorithm, which is a set of instructions that a computer follows to solve a problem. It's a measure of how long an algorithm takes to complete as the size of the input (n) increases. The notation is usually expressed as a function of n, and it's used to predict how an algorithm will perform on large inputs.\n\nHere's a ranking of the given notations from fastest to slowest:\n\n1. O(1) - This is the fastest, as it means the algorithm takes constant time, regardless of the size of the input. It's like looking up a value in an array by its index.\n2. O(log n) - This is faster than O(n) and O(n^2), as it means the algorithm takes time proportional to the logarithm of the input size. It's like searching a sorted array using a binary search.\n3. O(n) - This means the algorithm takes time proportional to the size of the input. It's like finding an element in an array by iterating through each element.\n4. O(n log n) - This is slower than O(n) but faster than O(n^2), as it means the algorithm takes time proportional to the product of the input size and its logarithm. It's like sorting an array using a merge sort.\n5. O(n^2) - This is slower than O(n) and O(n log n), as it means the algorithm takes time proportional to the square of the input size. It's like finding pairs of elements in an array that sum to a target value.\n6. O(2^n) - This is slower than O(n^2), as it means the algorithm takes time proportional to 2 raised to the power of the input size. It's like generating all possible subsets of a set.\n7. O(n!) - This is the slowest, as it means the algorithm takes time proportional to the factorial of the input size. It's like generating all possible permutations of a set.\n\n---VCP RATINGS---\nA (Analytical Precision): 9\nV (Verbal Fluency): 8\nG (Goal Directedness): 9\nP (Pattern Recognition): 8\nE (Epistemic Confidence): 9\nQ (Query Interpretation): 9\nC (Contextual Awareness): 8\nY (Affective Modeling): 6\nF (Flexibility): 8\nD (Depth of Processing): 9\n---END RATINGS---",
